Wed May 10 02:45:19 1995  Jonathan Kamens  <jik@annex-1-slip-jik.cam.ov.com>

	* XRn.src, patchlevel.h, xrn-man.src: Update version number for
	7.04-beta-1.

Wed May 10 02:22:04 1995  Jonathan Kamens  <jik@annex-1-slip-jik.cam.ov.com>

	* Imakefile: Add -DXRN to the symbols defined when compiling, so
	that modules which are written to work as part of XRN and
	independently of it know that they're being compiled as part of
	XRN.

	* allMode.c: Some calls to setButtonSensitive() which really only
	needed to happen once were happening every time all mode was
	entered.  They have been fixed to only happen when the all mode
	widgets are first created.

	* allMode.c: Some button/action functions which previously failed
	to verify that they were called from inside all mode now correctly
	verify this before performing their functions.

	* allMode.c, ngMode.c: The code which resets the groups selected
	for a later move operation is now called only when the displayed
	list of newsgroups actually changes.

 *	* artMode.c: Some button/action functions have been updated so
	that they will behave correctly when they are called when the
	subject cursor is on an article other than the currently displayed
	one.

	* Imakefile, InfoLine.c, InfoLine.h, addMode.c, allMode.c,
        artMode.c, ngMode.c: A new "InfoLine" interface for creating a
        one-line information label (usually to be placed inside a pane)
        has been added and is used to create information lines for the
        various modes.

	* XRn.src: In translations and accelerators, use symbolic names
	for keys, instead of their hexidecimal values.  In particular, use
	"space" instead of 0x20, "Linefeed" instead of 0xff0a, and
	"Return" instead of 0xff0d.

 *	* XRn.src, xrn-man.src: The key bindings for the various modes
	have been updated.  A few key bindings were changed or removed,
	but for the most part, the primary goal was to add new key
	bindings so that much more can be done without reaching for the
	mouse.  Furthermore, all default key bindings are now documented
	in the man page.

 *	* XRn.src, allMode.c, allMode.h, xrn-man.src: Two new buttons,
	"allNext" and "allPrev", have been added in all mode to move the
	cursor to the next or previous newsgroup.

	* XRn.src, mesg.c: Some resources that were hard-coded in mesg.c
	have been moved into XRn.src.

 *	* XRn.src, butexpl.h, xrn-man.src: New functionality has been
	added to make it possible to move around in the subject list in
	article mode without the displayed article following the subject
	cursor.  For the most part, this change will be transparent to
	people who don't want to use this functionality.  However, the one
	non-transparent aspect of it is that the up and down arrows no
	longer display the next and previous article; instead, they move
	the cursor without changing the displayed article.  The 'P' and
	'N' keys retain the behavior which used to be bound to the arrow
	keys.  Users who prefer the old behavior can restore it by putting
	the following in their X resources:

		xrn*artFrame.subjects.translations: #overrid	\n\
			~Meta<Key>Up:	artPrev()		\n\
			~Meta<Key>Down:	artNext()		\n

	For more information about this new functionality, see the
	documentation about it near the beginning of the "ARTICLE MODE"
	section of the man page.

	* TODO: Remove the item about adding and documenting key bindings,
	because it has been done.

	* TODO: Add an item about making attribution lines customizable.

	* TODO: Add an item about documenting the widget tree in the man
        page.

	* artMode.c, compose.c, dialogs.c, utils.h, xmisc.c: Some "gcc
	-Wall" nits have been eliminated by initializing variables that
	don't really need to be initialized, but that make gcc complain
	about them possibly being uninitialized.

	* ButtonBox.c, ButtonBox.h, Imakefile, addMode.c, allMode.c,
	artMode.c, butdefs.h, buttons.c, buttons.h, cancel.c, compose.c,
	mesg.c, ngMode.c: The generic button code has been revamped, so
	that there is a generic "ButtonBox" interface for creating a
	widget to contain a box of buttons and for adding buttons to it.

	* addMode.c, allMode.c, artMode.c, busyCursor.c, busyCursor.h,
	butdefs.h, internals.c, ngMode.c, xmisc.c, xmisc.h, xrn.c: The
	code which turns the mouse pointer into a watch when XRN is busy
	has been rewritten to use Xt commands to set the cursor, rather
	than using Xlib commands directly.

	* config.h, xrn.c: The title-bar functionality has been removed.
	Title bars are the responsibility of the window manager, not of
	XRN.

	* TODO, buttons.c, config.h: The DONT_FORCE_BUTTON_TRANSLATIONS
	and matchTranslations functionality has been removed.  It's not
	relevant as long as we're not supporting Motif, and when we do put
	Motif back, we can put it back in a more correct way, if
	necessary.

	* artMode.c, artMode.h: The various lists of buttons have been
	reordered to be in the same order as the man page's list.

 *	* XRn.src, addMode.c, addMode.h, allMode.c, allMode.h, artMode.c,
	artMode.h, buttons.c, buttons.h, compose.c, internals.c,
	internals.h, ngMode.c, ngMode.h, resources.c, resources.h,
	server.c, server.h, xrn-man.src, xrn.c, xrn.h: In previous
	versions of XRN, all modes used the widgets to display data in --
	the top text window, the top info line, the top button box, the
	bottom text window, the bottom info line, and the bottom button
	box.  This structure was problematic because it took advantage of
	available screen real estate poorly (why should part of the XRN
	window be blank and unused in all modes except article mode?).  It
	also made it difficult to maintain the code.  Therefore, the code
	has been reorganized so that each mode has its own "Paned" widget
	which fills the entire XRN window when the mode is active.  There
	are probably all kinds of little user-visible aspects of this
	change, but the big ones are: (1) Screen real estate is utilized
	more fully -- for example, in newsgroup mode, there's no longer a
	bottom text window, info line or button box, which means that many
	more newsgroups can be listed in the same space.  (2) The
	"Bindings" resources and command-line options have been removed.
	Instead, users should use the "translations" resources for the
	various modes in order to set bindings.  The correct resource to
	use for customizing each mode's translations is given in the
	documentation for that mode in the man page.  (3) Because each
	mode uses separate widgets, it is now possible to customize the
	appearance of modes separately -- for example, you can use
	different fonts for the newsgroup or article lists in different
	modes.  (4) Because the widget hierarchy has changed, the names of
	some widgets have changed, and therefore some user X resources
	which refer to those widgets might no longer work.  See the XRN
	source code or the application-defaults file to find out about the
	new names of the various widgets.

